		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Computer-aided design</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<dl>
<dd><i>"CAD", "CADD", and "ECAD" redirect here. For other uses see <a href="/wiki/CAD_(disambiguation)" title="CAD (disambiguation)">CAD (disambiguation)</a>, <a href="/wiki/CADD_(disambiguation)" title="CADD (disambiguation)">CADD (disambiguation)</a>, and <a href="/wiki/ECAD_(disambiguation)" title="ECAD (disambiguation)">ECAD (disambiguation)</a>.</i></dd>
</dl>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Cad_crank.jpg" class="image" title="An oblique view of a four-cylinder inline crankshaft with pistons."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Cad_crank.jpg/180px-Cad_crank.jpg" width="180" height="157" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Cad_crank.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
An oblique view of a four-cylinder inline crankshaft with pistons.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Computer-Aided Design</b> (<b>CAD</b>) is the use of computer technology to aid in the design and particularly the <a href="/wiki/Drafting" title="Drafting">drafting</a> (<a href="/wiki/Technical_drawing" title="Technical drawing">technical drawing</a> and <a href="/wiki/Engineering_drawing" title="Engineering drawing">engineering drawing</a>) of a part or product, including entire buildings. It is both a visual (or drawing) and symbol-based method of communication whose conventions are particular to a specific technical field.</p>
<p>Drafting can be done in <a href="/wiki/2D_computer_graphics" title="2D computer graphics">two dimensions</a> ("2D") and <a href="/wiki/3D_computer_graphics" title="3D computer graphics">three dimensions</a> ("3D").</p>
<p>Drafting is the communication of technical or engineering drawings and is the <a href="/wiki/Industrial_arts" title="Industrial arts">industrial arts</a> sub-discipline that underlies all involved technical endeavors. In representing complex, three-dimensional objects in two-dimensional drawings, these objects have traditionally been represented by three projected views at right angles.</p>
